","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 5: Monitor and Manage Copy Leaders","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"With Copy Trading, you could log off and keep a hands-free approach. However, its best to closely monitor your Copy Leader performance to allocate your capital effectively. Dont check in every hour or every day. Its normal for traders to run red days as well. Afterall, the best traders recover from drawdowns consistently.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"We recommend setting a trial period to give them time to perform and then reevaluate your decision. At the same time, dont be afraid to cut your losses as well. Whilst there isnt a golden rule, we recommend the following factors to evaluate your Copy Leaders performance:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"table","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"What to look for when evaluating","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"When to stop copy trading","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Is PnL trending upward?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}},{"nodeType":"text","value":" Yes, then its a good sign.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Expected range?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}},{"nodeType":"text","value":" If max drawdown is supposed to be -12% but you're at -50%, they might be deviating from strategy.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Has trading frequency changed dramatically?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}},{"nodeType":"text","value":" A scalper who suddenly makes 1 trade per week might have changed strategy.\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Hit your stop loss frequently","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Trader's strategy appears to have changed (fewer trades, different pairs, higher leverage)","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Drawdown exceeds their historical max by 20%+","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You need the capital for another opportunity","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"FAQ","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"How much does copy trading cost?","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Traders charge 0-50% profit share (you choose which traders to copy). BitMEX doesn't charge additional fees beyond standard trading fees.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"For example, if you profit $1,000 copying a trader who charges 15% profit share, you pay $150 to the trader and keep $850. If you lose money, you pay nothing.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Do I need a Hyperliquid account?","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"No. That's the entire point. You trade from BitMEX, copying traders who happen to be on Hyperliquid. No Web3 wallet, no bridging, no interactions with the complex DeFi world.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Can I copy multiple traders?","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Yes, up to 5 traders simultaneously. We recommend 3-5 for diversification. You can stop copying Copy Leaders any point in time and switch to a new trader.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"What if the trader loses money?","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Your account loses proportionally. This is why stop losses are mandatory. Set a -20% stop loss on every trader. Never commit capital youre not comfortable losing.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"What's the minimum to start?","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"$100 minimum to start copying a Copy Leader. However, Copy Leaders have the discretion to adjust the minimum capital to their preference. We recommend $500-1,000 to comfortably copy 2-3 traders.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Can I copy part of a trader's strategy?","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"No, you copy everything or nothing. You can't choose to only copy their BTC trades and skip ETH. This ensures strategy integrity.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"What happens if Hyperliquid goes offline?","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Your copy positions on BitMEX are unaffected. BitMEX operates independently of Hyperliquid. If a trader can't trade due to Hyperliquid downtime, your positions simply don't get new trades until they're back online.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},"category":"Trading Guides","categories":["Trading Guides"],"languageList":["English","British English"],"imageUrl":"https://images.ctfassets.net/4d5b2rvh73n7/11IDNDfMDE0syuTa4iqO5k/bef45d503dde58268e061bdb8290bfdf/image9.jpg","tags":[],"actualLocale":"en-US","seoMetaTitle":null,"seoMetaDescription":"Learn how to copy trade Hyperliquid's top traders on BitMEX. No wallet needed, start with $100.\n","customDisclaimer":null},{"id":"3J2ODOc72ho0d2y80cuOhu","title":"The Bitcoin Breakdown: Critical Levels to Watch","slug":"the-bitcoin-breakdown","publishDate":"2026-02-04T17:00:00.000+08:00","author":"BitMEX","excerpt":"Bitcoin faces a critical test at the $76,000 support level. Analyse the impact of Kevin Warshs Fed nomination and other structural shifts defining the 2026 market.","body":{"nodeType":"document","content":[{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Bitcoin has suffered a 15% contraction week-over-week. We have pierced critical levels, including Michael Saylors MSTR Bitcoin cost basis.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"While headlines focus on the immediate triggers such as Kevin Warshs nomination as Federal Reserve Chair, the structural rot that caused this crash began months ago.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"If you are looking at the charts wondering why the floor fell out or where the new supports are, here is the breakdown of the hidden 10 Oct Pivot and the three specific price levels that now define the market structure.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"The Fundamental Drivers Behind the Bitcoin Drop: ","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-3"},{"data":{"target":{"sys":{"id":"3fhiBhAC7JizjBUdsiO3aK","type":"Link","linkType":"Entry"}}},"content":[],"nodeType":"embedded-entry-block"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"The sell-off wasn't just a reaction to news, but rather a collapse of a market structure that has been fragile for months.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"1. The 10 Oct Pivot: Liquidation Cascade \u0026 Market Maker Wipeout","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"To understand why Bitcoin capitulated to $74,500 this weekend, you must look back to 10 October 2025. This date marks the moment the correlation between risk assets broke. Gold went parabolic while Bitcoin began a slow, confused bleed.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{"target":{"sys":{"id":"4bFL3C793ob0P2yFzqGKaF","type":"Link","linkType":"Entry"}}},"content":[],"nodeType":"embedded-entry-block"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Crucially, this period triggered a massive liquidation cascade that bankrupted many key market makers. As these liquidity providers were wiped out, order book depth evaporated. This left Bitcoin structurally weak, hollow, and propped up only by fragile ETF inflows and leverage. When the macro environment shifted this week, the buffer usually provided by market makers did not exist to absorb the selling.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"2. The Kevin Warsh Nomination","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"On 30 January, President Trump nominated Kevin Warsh as Federal Reserve Chair. Warsh represents a hawkish regime shift focused on balance sheet reduction. This signaled to the market that the Federal Reserve would no longer support the debasement trade that had propelled asset prices higher, causing an immediate repricing of risk.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"3. The Liquidity Fear From Government Shutdown","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"The final blow was the US government shutdown. With government operations halted, the market was gripped by a fear that the flow of new liquidity into the economy would completely stop.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Combined with Warshs nomination, the government shutdown created a worst-case scenario: a government that cannot spend and a central bank that refuses to print. This fear of no new liquidity caused capital to freeze. Investors fled to cash. Without new money entering the system to support prices, the hollowed-out crypto market collapsed.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"The 3 Critical Levels for BTC","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-3"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Now that the leverage has been flushed (with over $2.5 billion in liquidations in a single weekend), we are left with a scarred chart. If you look at the price action specifically, the market is currently trapped between three distinct psychological zones.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"The Saylor Line (Current Support: ~$76,000)","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"The first and most immediate battleground is roughly $76,031. This is the estimated average cost basis of MicroStrategys massive Bitcoin treasury.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"For the first time in this cycle, Michael Saylors position is teetering on the edge of being underwater. The market knows this. The weekend wick down to $74,500 was a stop huntpredatory traders trying to push the price low enough to trigger panic. But the line held.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"As long as Bitcoin trades above this level, the corporate balance sheet narrative remains intact. If we lose this level for a sustained period, the psychological damage to retail investorswho view Saylor as the invincible bullcould be severe.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"The Spot ETF Wall (Resistance: ~$84,000)","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" ","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"If the Saylor Line is the floor, the ETF Wall is the ceiling. The $84,000 to $85,000 range represents the cost basis for the billions of dollars that flowed into the US Spot ETFs over the last quarter.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"These investors are not crypto natives. They are asset allocators and retirees. Right now, they are sitting on a loss. Human psychology dictates that when the price rallies back to their entry price, they will sell to get out at breakeven. This creates a massive wall of supply overhead. Until Bitcoin can decisively reclaim $84,000 and turn those holders back into profit, any rally is likely to be sold into.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"2021 All-Time High at $69,000","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" ","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"If the contagion from the metals market continues and the Saylor Line breaks, there is only one level that matters: $69,000. This is the 2021 All-Time High. It is the structural line in the sand for the entire multi-year bull market. A retest of this level would be painful. However, historically, retesting a previous cycle high is a generational buying opportunity.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"What to Look Out For Next","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-3"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"As of today, the government shutdown has been resolved. However, Bitcoin remains in a precarious position. While traditional safe havens are bouncing, crypto is lagging. Heres what you need to watch:","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"The Lag Signal (Gold vs. Bitcoin)","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" ","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"While Gold and Silver have rallied back strongly following the shutdown resolution, Bitcoin is still stuck in the mud, hovering near $78,000. This divergence is the most critical signal to watch. If metals continue to soar while Bitcoin stagnates, it confirms that the liquidity vacuum in crypto is specific to the asset class (market maker failure) rather than just general macro fear. Bitcoin must catch up to the metals rally within the next 48 hours to confirm a bottom.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"ETF Outflows vs. Stabilisation","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" ","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"With the shutdown fear resolved, do ETF investors buy the dip or sell into the relief? Watch the daily flow data. If we see sustained outflows despite the government reopening, it suggests institutional confidence has been shaken by the Warsh nomination regardless of fiscal spending.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"value":"The $76k Double Tap","nodeType":"text"},{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":" ","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"heading-5"},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"The market often tests a low twice. Expect a potential retest of the MicroStrategy cost basis ($76,052). If this level holds on a second test while Gold remains strong, it is a high-conviction buy signal. If it fails, the path to $69,000 opens up immediately.","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"}]},"category":"BitMEX Alpha","categories":["BitMEX Alpha"],"languageList":["English","Russian","Chinese Simplified","Dutch","French","German","Hindi","Japanese","Korean","Spanish","Turkish","Vietnamese","British English"],"imageUrl":"https://images.ctfassets.net/4d5b2rvh73n7/3im026krGQlFJm6sGzKXhf/b41e4345b543b18a52145203b9f88cb8/BTCBreakdown_Social.png","tags":[],"actualLocale":"en-US","seoMetaTitle":null,"seoMetaDescription":"Bitcoin faces a critical test at the $76,000 support level. Analyse the impact of Kevin Warshs Fed nomination and other structural shifts defining the 2026 market.","customDisclaimer":null},{"id":"39cQdWSNQvdGCiOpvqY2WW","title":"Leverage Trading in Crypto: What It Is, How It Works \u0026 Risks","slug":"what-is-leverage-trade","publishDate":"2026-02-03T00:00:00.000+08:00","author":"BitMEX","excerpt":"What is leverage trading? How to trade and potential risks.","body":{"nodeType":"document","content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Key Takeaways","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Leverage trading crypto amplifies your buying power, allowing you to control positions worth $10,000 with just $1,000 in capital  but losses are magnified equally.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Margin trading borrows real assets and charges interest, futures contracts use synthetic leverage with funding rates instead.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Liquidation is the biggest threat: at 100x leverage, a mere 1% price move against you wipes out your entire position.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Smart traders use isolated margin, strict stop-losses, and never risk more than 1-2% of capital per trade.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"BitMEX offers up to 100x leverage on perpetual and traditional futures across Bitcoin, Ethereum, and altcoins, with tools designed for capital efficient trading.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"What Is Leverage in Crypto?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Leverage is essentially a multiplier for your buying power. Its extremely capital efficient when trading crypto as it lets you control a position far larger than your account balance.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Here's how it works in practice: you want exposure to $10,000 worth of Bitcoin, but you only have $1,000. By using 10x crypto leverage, you can open that full $10,000 position whilst your $1,000 acts as collateral (margin). If Bitcoin rises 5%, you gain 5% on the full $10,000 (that's $500 profit, a 50% return on your $1,000).","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"But here's the catch, leverage is a double edged sword. Your gains are amplified but so are your losses. If your position drops 10%? Your position is liquidated and automatically closed.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"This is why understanding what is leverage trading crypto isn't optional  it's survival.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"How Leverage Works: The Mechanics","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Crypto trading with leverage isn't magic. It's a contractual agreement where the exchange (or other traders) lends you capital, secured by your collateral. Here's the step-by-step flow of setting up your leverage position:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 1: Initial Margin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You deposit collateral for your trade, such as USDT, Bitcoin, or other accepted assets. Think of this as your skin in the game. The amount required depends on your chosen leverage ratio.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Example: To open a $10,000 position at 10x leverage, you need $1,000 in margin (10% of the position size).","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 2: Exchange Provides Leverage","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"BitMEX (or any exchange) effectively provides the remaining $9,000. You now control $10,000 worth of Bitcoin whilst only risking $1,000 of your own capital.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 3: PnL Is Calculated on the Full Position","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Beginners usually forget this point. If Bitcoin moves 3%, your PnL is calculated on $10,000, not $1,000. That's $300 gained or lost (a 30% swing on your margin).","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 4: Know Your Maintenance Margin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Exchanges require you to maintain a minimum equity level in your position, called the maintenance margin. Derived from its name, its the minimum amount of margin you have to maintain. Else, if your losses eat into your margin and you fall below this threshold, your position gets liquidated. As the exchange is lending you capital, they have to protect their assets as well. The exchange closes your position to prevent you owing them money.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 5: Funding Fees (Perps)","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"The beauty of trading crypto perpetual swaps is they never expire. This is due to a funding rate mechanism which anchors the perps price and the spot price. A funding fee is exchanged between longs and shorts, usually paid in regular intervals. (e.g. every 8 hours)","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"During bull runs, longs pay shorts. This cost is calculated on your full position size, not just your margin. So high funding rates can slowly bleed your equity even if the price stays flat. Learn more about funding fees ","marks":[],"data":{}},{"nodeType":"hyperlink","data":{"uri":"https://www.bitmex.com/blog/2025q3-derivatives-report"},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"here.","marks":[{"type":"underline"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"text","value":"","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Pro Tip: Funding rates are paid every eight hours. If you're trading during a high funding rate period, funding costs can exceed 100% annualised, which depletes your position margin and pulls up your liquidation price. Check the funding rate before entering a position, especially during euphoric rallies.\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Margin vs Futures: What's Different?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Although both let you trade with crypto leverage, the mechanics are worlds apart. Here's what you need to know:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Margin Trading","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Think of this as a loan. You're borrowing real assets and you pay interest on that loan. When you margin trade, you own actual Bitcoin. Meaning your PnL happens in the spot market.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Cost: Interest rate (hourly or daily).","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Who you pay: The exchange or liquidity providers.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Regulation: Heavily restricted in many jurisdictions. In the US, for example, it's limited to Eligible Contract Participants: (individuals with over $7M in assets).","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Leverage limits: Typically lower than futures, around 3x to 5x.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Futures Trading","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"In the traditional finance world, a future contract is an agreement to buy or sell an underlying asset at a predetermined price at a specified date. However, in crypto, the market is dominated by Perpetual Swaps, which are future contracts that have no expiration date.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You don't own Bitcoin. Instead, you own a contract that mirrors Bitcoin's price movements. Meaning the leverage is synthetic as there are no assets are borrowed.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Cost: Funding rate (perpetuals) or no ongoing fee (traditional futures with expiry dates).","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Who you pay: Other traders. If longs outnumber shorts, longs pay shorts, and vice versa.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Regulation: More accessible globally (though US restrictions still apply).","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Leverage limits: Much higher - often 50x, 100x, or even 200x.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"BitMEX pioneered this mechanism back in 2016 that changed the crypto trading game forever. Perpetual futures is probably the best innovation in cryptos past decade. Its the most popular derivative for leverage trading crypto, accounting roughly 80%+ of the total crypto trading volume.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Margin vs Futures: Comparison Table","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"table","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Feature","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Margin Trading","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Perpetual Futures","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Traditional Futures","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Asset Ownership","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You own real crypto","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You own a price tracking contract","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You own a price tracking contract","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Cost Type","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Interest rate","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Funding rate (usually every 8 hours)","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"No ongoing fee","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Who You Pay","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Exchange/lenders","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Other traders (Longs  Shorts)","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"N/A (settled at expiry)","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Leverage Limits","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Usually low, max 5x","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Up to 200x","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"50x-125x","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Expiry","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"None","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"None","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Monthly or Quarterly","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-row","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Regulation","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Heavily restricted","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"More accessible","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"table-cell","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"More accessible","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Calculations You Must Know","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Before you place a leveraged trade, you need to calculate three things manually: your exposure, your PnL, and your liquidation distance. These aren't theoretical exercisesthey're survival tools.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"1. Total Market Exposure","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"This tells you how much you're actually controlling.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Formula: Total Exposure = Investment Amount  Leverage Ratio","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Example: You invest $500 at 10x leverage. Total Exposure = $500  10 = $5,000","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You're now controlling $5,000 worth of Bitcoin. If BTC moves 2%, your PnL is calculated on $5,000, not $500.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"2. Profit and Loss (PnL) with Leverage","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Your gains and losses are calculated on your total position, not your margin.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Example:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You have $1,000 margin.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"You use 10x leverage to open a $10,000 position.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Bitcoin rises 5%.\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Your Profit: 5% of $10,000 = $500 (a 50% return on your $1,000 capital).","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"If Bitcoin falls 5%: Your Loss: 5% of $10,000 = $500 (a 50% loss of your $1,000 capital).","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"3. Liquidation Distance","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"This is the price movement (percentage) required to trigger liquidation.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Formula (simplified): Liquidation Distance  1 / Leverage","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Example:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"10x leverage: 1 / 10 = 10% move liquidates you.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"50x leverage: 1 / 50 = 2% move liquidates you.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"100x leverage: 1 / 100 = 1% move liquidates you.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Real-world application: You enter Bitcoin at $40,000 using 10x leverage on a long position. Liquidation Distance = 10% Liquidation Price  $40,000 - ($40,000  10%) = $36,000","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Note: Actual liquidation happens slightly before this price because exchanges require a maintenance margin buffer (typically 0.5-1% of position size). This protects the exchange from losses if the market moves too fast.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Pro Tip: Don't rely on the exchange's liquidation calculator alone. Do the maths yourself before entering a trade. If your liquidation price is within a range Bitcoin regularly wicks to during volatility (e.g. 10% below current price), you're over-leveraged. Reduce your position size or use lower leverage.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Risks \u0026 How to Manage Them","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Leverage trading crypto isn't inherently reckless  instead, it punishes recklessness. Here's how to survive.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"1. Liquidation Risk (The Big One)","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"If the market moves against you and your equity falls below the maintenance margin, the exchange auto-closes your position. Your collateral is gone.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"How to manage it:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Use lower leverage. Beginners should stick to 2x3x maximum.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Set a stop-loss order. This exits your position before liquidation is triggered. Non-negotiable.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Monitor your margin ratio. Most exchanges show this in real-time. If it's dropping, add margin or close the position manually.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Real-world context: Imagine you're long Ethereum at 20x leverage. A flash crash drops ETH 6% in minutes. You're liquidated before you can react. Even if ETH rebounds 10 minutes later, you're out. Gone. This happens daily in crypto. Isolated margin limits this damage to one position; cross margin can drain your entire account.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"2. Volatility and \"Wick\" Risk","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Crypto markets run 24/7 and are notoriously volatile. \"Scam wicks\"momentary price spikes caused by low liquidity or cascading liquidationscan trigger your stop-loss or liquidate you, even if price returns to normal seconds later.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"How to manage it:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Place stop-losses slightly wider than your liquidation price to account for wicks.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Avoid maximum leverage (100x) on illiquid altcoins.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Trade during high-liquidity periods (e.g., during US/EU market hours).","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"3. Funding Fee Drag (Perpetuals)","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"If you're holding a long position during a bull run, you'll pay funding fees to shorts every eight hours. These fees are calculated on your full leveraged position, not your margin. Over days or weeks, they erode your equity and pull your liquidation price closer.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"How to manage it:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Check the funding rate before entering a trade. If it's above 0.1% per interval, consider waiting or using lower leverage.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Close positions before funding intervals if you're day trading.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Switch to traditional futures (with expiry dates) if funding is consistently high. These have no funding fees.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"4. Isolated vs Cross Margin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"This choice determines whether one bad trade nukes your entire account or just the allocated collateral.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Isolated Margin (Recommended): Limits risk to the collateral assigned to that specific trade. If you allocate $500 to a long position and it goes underwater, you lose $500. The rest of your wallet is safe.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Cross Margin (Dangerous): Uses your entire account balance as collateral for all positions. If one position fails, the exchange draws from your main balance to prevent liquidation. Sounds usefuluntil a market-wide crash causes your loss on your BTC long to eat the collateral meant for your ETH trade. Even with a stop-loss, the speed of the crash can cause a failing position to wipe out your entire margin.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Pro Tip: ","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}},{"nodeType":"text","value":"For most traders, isolated margin is the safer default. Under cross margin, your positions are \"linked.\" Imagine a market-wide crash: your loss on your XBT long begins eating the collateral meant for your ETH long trade. Even with a stop-loss, the speed of the crash can cause a failing position to wipe out your entire margin.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"How to Place a Leveraged Trade on BitMEX (Five Steps)","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Here's how to put crypto leverage trading into practice on BitMEX.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 1: Choose Your Market","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Navigate to the \"Trade\" tab and select your market. BitMEX offers perpetual and traditional futures on Bitcoin (XBTUSD), Ethereum (ETHUSD), and a range of altcoins. Perpetuals have no expiry; traditional futures settle monthly or quarterly.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"embedded-entry-block","data":{"target":{"sys":{"id":"1e9yFa8crpGf4YNx2f3wrm","type":"Link","linkType":"Entry"}}},"content":[]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 2: Select Your Leverage","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Use the leverage slider to choose your multiplier (1x to 100x). Start conservative2x to 5x for beginners. Remember: higher leverage = smaller liquidation distance.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"embedded-entry-block","data":{"target":{"sys":{"id":"6pMUzU6qh4suqJrh2cZ6oB","type":"Link","linkType":"Entry"}}},"content":[]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Pro Tip: Even if you set 100x leverage, you don't have to use it. You can open a small position (e.g. $100 out of $10,000 balance) at 100x, which creates the same dollar risk as a $1,000 position at 10x. Leverage is a tool for capital efficiency, not a risk dial.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 3: Set Isolated or Cross Margin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Toggle \"Isolated Margin\" in the leverage panel. This puts your risk to the collateral you allocate. If the trade goes wrong, only that margin is at stake  not your entire account.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"embedded-entry-block","data":{"target":{"sys":{"id":"3bh99B1WYaFrxneF9hSgKl","type":"Link","linkType":"Entry"}}},"content":[]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 4: Enter Your Order Details","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Order Type: Market (instant execution) or Limit (you set the price).","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Quantity: The number of contracts","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Stop-Loss: Set this before you place the trade. Decide your exit price if the market moves against you. BitMEX supports stop-market and stop-limit orders.","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"embedded-entry-block","data":{"target":{"sys":{"id":"ZWNTKLyZO6IcvElOMMKjE","type":"Link","linkType":"Entry"}}},"content":[]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Example: You're bullish on Bitcoin at $40,000. You set a stop-loss at $38,000 (5% risk). If BTC drops to $38,000, your position auto-closes. You've capped your loss.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Step 5: Monitor Funding (Perpetuals Only)","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"If you've entered a perpetual contract, check the funding rate (shown at the top of the trading page). If it's positive and you're long, you'll pay shorts every eight hours. Budget for this cost, especially if you're holding multi-day positions.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"embedded-entry-block","data":{"target":{"sys":{"id":"VSVlrdt3nCLGSbS7gslov","type":"Link","linkType":"Entry"}}},"content":[]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"FAQ","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"1. What is leverage trading crypto?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Leverage trading crypto is a method that allows you to control a position larger than your account balance by using borrowed capital. For example, 10x leverage lets you control $10,000 of Bitcoin with just $1,000 in margin. Gains and losses are calculated on the full $10,000, magnifying both profit and risk.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"2. Is crypto leverage trading legal?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"It depends on your jurisdiction. In the UK and most of Europe, crypto trading with leverage is legal but regulated. Exchanges must comply with FCA rules (UK) or MiCA (EU). In the United States, leverage on crypto derivatives is heavily restricted for retail traders. Always check your local laws before trading.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"3. What's the difference between margin and futures leverage?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Margin trading borrows real assets (e.g., USDT or BTC) and charges interest. Futures leverage uses contracts that track priceyou don't borrow or own the underlying asset. Futures (especially perpetuals) typically offer higher leverage (up to 100x) and charge funding rates instead of interest.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"4. How much leverage should a beginner use?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Start with 2x to 5x maximum. This gives you room to survive market swings whilst you learn position sizing, stop-losses, and risk management. High leverage (50x100x) is a tool for experienced traders who understand the liquidation risks and use it for capital efficiency, not to gamble.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"5. Can I lose more than my initial margin?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"On most exchanges, noisolated margin limits your loss to the collateral you allocate. However, during extreme volatility (flash crashes, gaps), slippage can cause your loss to exceed your margin slightly. This is rare but possible. Cross margin increases this risk significantly, as it can drain your entire account balance.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"6. What is a funding rate, and why does it matter?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"The funding rate is a periodic fee exchanged between longs and shorts on perpetual futures to keep the contract price aligned with the spot price. If the market is bullish, longs pay shorts (and vice versa). This fee is calculated on your full leveraged position and charged every eight hours. High funding rates can erode your margin over time, even if price doesn't move.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"7. How do I avoid liquidation?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Set a stop-loss order before entering the trade, use low leverage (2x5x for beginners), enable isolated margin, and never risk more than 12% of your account on a single trade. Monitor your margin ratio and add collateral if it's dropping toward the maintenance threshold.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"8. Does BitMEX offer leverage on all assets?","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"BitMEX offers leveraged perpetual and traditional futures on Bitcoin, Ethereum, and select altcoins. Leverage limits vary by asset (up to 100x on XBTUSD). The platform also offers leveraged products on gold and equity indices, giving you cross-asset opportunities beyond crypto.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Glossary","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Margin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"The collateral you deposit to open and maintain a leveraged position. Your \"skin in the game.\" If your margin falls below the maintenance threshold, you're liquidated.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Isolated Margin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"A margin mode that ring-fences the collateral for a specific trade. If that trade goes underwater, only the allocated margin is lostnot your entire account balance. Recommended for most traders.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Cross Margin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"A margin mode that uses your entire account balance as collateral for all open positions. If one trade fails, the exchange draws from your main balance to prevent liquidation. High risk: a single bad trade can drain your entire wallet.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Maintenance Margin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"The minimum equity you must maintain in a position to avoid liquidation. Typically 0.5%1% of the position size. If your losses push you below this threshold, the exchange auto-closes your position.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Mark Price","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"The fair value of a contract, calculated using a weighted average of spot exchange prices. BitMEX uses mark price (not the last traded price) to trigger liquidations. This protects traders from manipulation and \"scam wicks\" on low-liquidity contracts.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Funding Rate","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"A periodic payment exchanged between longs and shorts on perpetual futures (every eight hours). If the perpetual price is above the spot price, longs pay shorts. If it's below, shorts pay longs. This mechanism tethers the futures price to the spot market.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"heading-3","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Bankruptcy Price","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"The price at which your position's loss equals 100% of your initial margin. Liquidation is triggered before this point (at the maintenance margin level) to protect the exchange from negative equity.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"\n","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},"category":"Trading Guides","categories":["Trading Guides"],"languageList":["English","British English"],"imageUrl":"https://images.ctfassets.net/4d5b2rvh73n7/6KERFJIXwvxQ3TDtwoHAcZ/92060dd9b7f9429a147a367b20f62b7f/leveragetrading.jpg","tags":[],"actualLocale":"en-US","seoMetaTitle":null,"seoMetaDescription":"What is leverage trading? How to trade and potential risks.","customDisclaimer":null},{"id":"60GHXETw9S4OTPAujHqlXm","title":"What Is Ethereum? The Complete 2026 Guide","slug":"what-is-ethereum","publishDate":"2026-01-30T00:00:00.000+08:00","author":"BitMEX","excerpt":"What Is Ethereum? Ethereum  is the world's second-largest cryptocurrency by market cap (after Bitcoin) but it isnt just a crypto currency. Its more of a super computer. Here's the real definition: Ethereum is a global, decentralised computer that runs applications without downtime, censorship, or third-party control. Think of it this way: Bitcoin  = Digital money (you can send/receive BTC) Ethereum  = Digital money + programmable smart contracts (you can build apps, DeFi protocols, NFTs, DAOs, and entire financial systems) The Simplest Analogy: Bitcoin : A calculator that only does one thing, send/receive money. Ethereum : A smartphone that runs thousands of apps (DeFi, NFTs, games, DAOs) AND sends/receive money (ETH).  Every major crypto innovation since 2017 runs on Ethereum: DeFi  (Uniswap, Aave, MakerDAO) = Built on Ethereum NFTs  (Bored Apes, CryptoPunks, OpenSea) = Built on Ethereum Stablecoins  (USDC, USDT, DAI) = Built on Ethereum (or Ethereum-based chains) DAOs  (decentralized organizations) = Built on Ethereum Pro Tip : Don't think of Ethereum as Bitcoin's competitor. They're solving different problems. Bitcoin is money. Ethereum is infrastructure. You need both to run the world. How Does Ethereum Actually Work? The Basics: Ethereum = Blockchain + Smart Contracts Blockchain : A public ledger that records every transaction ever made. Think of it as Google Sheets, but: No one owns it (decentralized across 1 million+ computers) No one can edit history (immutable) Everyone can view it (transparent) Smart Contracts : Self-executing programs that run on the blockchain. Real-World Scenario:  Imagine you want to lend $10,000 USDC and earn 5% interest. Traditionally: Go to a bank  They say no (they dont deal with crypto) Find a P2P lending platform  They take 3% fees Wait 7 days for KYC approval Hope the borrower pays you back On Ethereum (using Aave): Open Aave.com (a DeFi lending protocol) Connect your MetaMask wallet Deposit your 10,000 USDC Smart contract automatically matches you with borrowers You start earning 5% APY instantly Withdraw anytime (might have a unstake period) Pro Tip : Ethereum smart contracts are public, anyone can audit the code. Before using a DeFi protocol, check if it's been audited by firms like CertiK or Trail of Bits. Unaudited contracts = high risk of exploits.\n Ethereum vs Bitcoin: What's the Actual Difference? Here's the honest breakdown: Feature Bitcoin Ethereum Launch Year 2009 2015 Purpose Digital currency Programmable platform Max Supply 21 million BTC No hard cap (but issuance is capped post-Merge) Transaction Speed 7 TPS 15 TPS (30-100 TPS on Layer 2s) Smart Contracts No (limited scripting) Yes (Turing complete) Use Cases Store of value, payments DeFi, NFTs, DAOs, games, identity Market Cap ~$1.6 trillion (as of 30 Jan 2026) ~$300 billion (as of 30 Jan 2026) Inflation Rate ~0.7% (halving every 4 years) ~0.5% (after The Merge) Consensus Proof of Work (mining) Proof of Stake (staking)  The Key Difference: Bitcoin : Optimized for security and scarcity. It does one thing (money) and does it perfectly. Ethereum : Optimized for flexibility and programmability. It does many things (DeFi, NFTs, apps) but trades off some security and decentralization. Which Is Better?  They're complementary: Hold Bitcoin for long-term wealth preservation (it's not going anywhere) Use Ethereum for earning yield (DeFi staking), trading (perpetuals on Ethereum-based DEXs), and exposure to the crypto app economy\n What Is Ether (ETH)? The Fuel of the Ethereum Network Ether (ETH)  is Ethereum's native cryptocurrency. You need ETH to: Pay transaction fees  (called gas fees) Deploy smart contracts Stake and secure the network  Trade on DEXs  (ETH is the base pair for most token swaps) Think of ETH as: Bitcoin = gold  (you hold it for value) ETH = oil  (you use it to power the entire Ethereum economy) How ETH Issuance Works (Post-Merge) Before September 2022, Ethereum used Proof of Work (mining). Miners earned new ETH for securing the network. Inflation was ~4.3% per year. After  The Merge  (Ethereum's switch to Proof of Stake in 2022): No more mining   Miners are gone Stakers earn rewards   Lock up 32 ETH to validate transactions, earn ~3-5% APY ETH often became deflationary   When network usage is high, more ETH is burned than issued\n Real Numbers (2024 Data): ETH issued annually : ~800,000 ETH ETH burned annually : ~1.2 million ETH (via EIP-1559) Net effect : -400,000 ETH per year (~-0.5% deflation) The Ethereum Merge: Why September 2022 Changed Everything The Merge  was Ethereum's transition from  Proof of Work (mining)  to  Proof of Stake (staking) . Why It Mattered: 99.95% energy reduction  (Ethereum went from consuming as much energy as Austria to as much as a small town) ETH became deflationary  (supply shrank instead of inflated) Validator rewards replaced mining rewards  (you can now earn ETH by staking, not just mining) Before The Merge: Ethereum miners (people running GPUs) secured the network High energy usage (similar to Bitcoin's mining) After The Merge: Stakers (people locking up 32 ETH) secure the network Energy usage dropped 99.95% \n The Result:  Ethereum became the first major blockchain to go from Proof of Work to Proof of Stake without forking, without breaking, and without losing security. What Are Ethereum Gas Fees? \n Gas fees  are the cost of using Ethereum. Every transaction (sending ETH, swapping tokens, minting NFTs) requires computational power. Validators charge fees to process these transactions. Why Fees Get Expensive:  Ethereum can only process ~15 transactions per second (TPS). When demand spikes (like during an NFT mint or DeFi craze), users bid up gas fees to get their transactions processed first. Real Example: Normal day : Sending ETH costs $1-5 NFT mint day (high demand) : Sending ETH costs $50-200 Peak DeFi craze (2021) : Swapping tokens on Uniswap cost $100-300 Why This Happens:  Think of Ethereum as a highway with only 15 lanes. When 10,000 cars want to use it simultaneously, they bid for space. The highest bidders get through first. The solution? Layer 2 Scaling Ethereum's roadmap includes Layer 2 networks (Arbitrum, Optimism, Base, Polygon) that bundle hundreds of transactions and settle them on Ethereum's mainnet. This reduces fees by 90-99%. Current State (2024-2026): Ethereum mainnet : $5-50 per transaction (expensive) Arbitrum/Optimism : $0.10-1 per transaction (cheap) Base (Coinbase's L2) : $0.05-0.50 per transaction (cheapest) Pro Tip : Don't trade on Ethereum mainnet unless you're moving $10K+. Use Layer 2s for small transactions. Your $100 trade shouldn't cost $30 in gas fees.   FAQ Can Ethereum overtake Bitcoin? In market cap? Unlikely. In utility? It already has. They serve different purposes. Is Ethereum proof of stake or proof of work? Proof of Stake (since September 2022, after The Merge). How many Ethereum are there? In early 2026, roughly ~120 million ETH in circulation. No hard cap, but issuance is low (~0.5% annual inflation, often deflationary). Can Ethereum go to $10,000? Possible. Would require $1.2 trillion market cap (vs. current $500B). It would require continued adoption and institutional inflows.","body":{"nodeType":"document","content":[{"nodeType":"heading-2","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"What Is Ethereum?","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Ethereum","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}},{"nodeType":"text","value":" is the world's second-largest cryptocurrency by market cap (after Bitcoin) but it isnt just a crypto currency. Its more of a super computer.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Here's the real definition: Ethereum is a global, decentralised computer that runs applications without downtime, censorship, or third-party control.","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Think of it this way:","marks":[],"data":{}}]},{"nodeType":"unordered-list","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Bitcoin","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}},{"nodeType":"text","value":" = Digital money (you can send/receive BTC)","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]},{"nodeType":"list-item","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"paragraph","data":{},"content":[{"nodeType":"text","value":"Ethereum","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"data":{}},{"nodeType":"text","value":" = Digital money + programmable smart contracts (you can build apps, DeFi protocols, NFTs, DAOs, and entire financial systems)","marks":[],"data":{}}]}]}]},{"nodeType":"paragra